# Python Testing

## pytest Conventions
- Name test files `test_*.py` and test functions `test_*`
- Use `pytest.fixture` for shared setup, prefer function scope
- Use `tmp_path` fixture for file system tests (auto-cleaned)
- Group related tests in classes: `class TestUserAuth:`

## Assertions
- Use plain `assert` with descriptive messages: `assert result == 42, f"Expected 42, got {result}"`
- Use `pytest.raises(ExceptionType, match="pattern")` for expected errors
- Use `pytest.approx()` for floating-point comparisons

## Structure
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert pattern
- One assertion per test when possible (multiple is fine if testing one behavior)
- Test names should describe the scenario: `test_login_fails_with_expired_token`
- Keep tests independent — no shared mutable state between tests

## Mocking
- Use `unittest.mock.patch` or `pytest-mock`'s `mocker` fixture
- Mock at the boundary (external APIs, databases, clocks)
- Prefer dependency injection over monkey-patching
- Always verify mock calls: `mock.assert_called_once_with(...)`

## Coverage
- Aim for >80% line coverage on business logic
- Don't chase 100% — focus on critical paths and edge cases
- Test error paths and boundary conditions, not just happy paths
